<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-712-484  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 712 484.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Systems News  August 6 1990 n478 p1(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Brave new databases: object orientation gains steam. (includesrelated article on the emergence of standards for object-orienteddatabases)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Greenbaum, Joshua.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Systems integrators are starting to take interest inobject-oriented data base technology for building powerful,easy-to-use and develop data bases.andP;  Andersen Consulting isstudying the technology while DEC is reportedly investing in anobject-oriented data base startup.andP;  There are pros and cons to thenew technology.andP;  On the plus side, object-oriented data companiesare integrating CAD-CAM and imaging technology.andP;  They are showingthat there are whole areas of mission-critical applications thatrelational data bases are unable to solve.andP;  Fortunately,relational data bases, which are still the norm, are notincompatible with object-oriented data bases.andP;  On the minus side,however, it is very costly to convert from relational data basesto object-oriented data bases, a procedure which corporations feelmay be necessary.andP;  It will be up to the object-oriented companies,which are small and new, to effect market acceptance.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Object-Oriented Data BasesMarket PenetrationIndustry AnalysisSoftware ArchitectureRelational Data BasesVendors.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>